{
  "texts": [
    "On top of that, many of the current rules in the AIA -such as those relating to general-purpose AI and the systemic risk category -require detailed interpretation by the European Commission and the AI Office.",
    "Such delegation of powers comes with challenges to democratic legitimacy, as the actual decisions will eventually be taken by technocrats and not elected representatives.",
    "To name just one example to illustrate the challenge that comes with this approach, the phase-out process of the incandescent light bulb technology between 2009 and 2013 was based on broad guidelines set in the so-called Eco-Design directive adopted by the legislators and further interpreted and implemented by the EU Commission.",
    "Once regular citizens realised they needed to get rid of their seemingly beloved (conventional) lightbulbs -because \"the Commission\" decided this -and replace them with more energy-efficient versions, this sparked a significant backlash policy-makers had to deal with (Stegmaier et al., 2021, pp. 16-19).",
    "The legislators might have learned from this experience since Article 97 AIA contains reporting duties for the Commission, a potential sunset period for power delegation of five years, as well as the possibility of revoking the powers from the Commission for both the Parliament and the Council."
  ]
}